        }
        input, textarea {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 8px;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .result {
            margin-top: 20px;
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Simple Form Example</h2>
        <form id="simpleForm" action="/submit-form" method="post">
            <div class="form-group">
                <label for="username">Username:</label>
                <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required>
            </div>
            <div class="form-group">
                <label for="email">Email:</label>
                <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>
            </div>
            <button type="submit">Submit</button>
        </form>
        <div id="result" class="result"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        document.getElementById('simpleForm').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
            event.preventDefault(); // Prevent the default form submission

            const username = document.getElementById('username').value;
            const email = document.getElementById('email').value;

            // Send the data to the server
            fetch('/submit-form', {
                method: 'POST',
                headers: {
                    'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded',
                },
                body: `username=${username}&email=${email}`
            })
            .then(response => response.text())
            .then(data => {
                document.getElementById('result').innerText = data;
            })
            .catch(error => console.error('Error:', error));
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation

1. **Server Setup**:
   - We use Express to create a simple web server.
   - We connect to an in-memory SQLite database using `sqlite3`.
   - We create a table named `users` to store the form data.
   - We define a route to handle POST requests at `/submit-form`. This route inserts the form data into the database and returns a success message.

2. **HTML Form**:
   - The form now uses the `action` attribute to point to the `/submit-form` endpoint.
   - The form data is sent via a `POST` request using the `fetch` API.
   - The result is displayed in the `result` div.

### Running the Project

1. **Start the Server**:
   ```sh
   node server.js
   ```

2. **Open the HTML File**:
   - Open the `index.html` file in a web browser.
   - Fill out the form and submit it.
   - The server will save the data to the SQLite database and display a confirmation message.

This setup provides a complete cycle from user input to data handling and storage, giving your intern a practical understanding of how forms work in a real-world scenario.

